<div class="comment" id="comment_69965">


<b>Alan Moore</b><br/>


<span class="sub">Feb 10, 2015  11:36pm</span>
	
	<p><p>Great article: I'd like to add that even in the age of CDs and digital it's not straightforward to own Agharta and Pangaea. In 1990, as part of the abhorred Jazz Masterpiece series, the two albums were put out on CD (in those 'fat' double CD cases you used to get) and they are of an inferior, but not unlistenable, quality. Nowhere near as good as the Japanese LPs. Those are the only officially released version in the USA.</p>

<p>In Japan there have been two versions of each album: one representing the full sets as played, with no extra production. They're both longer -- one album by a couple of seconds, the other by more than 10 minutes. They also sound nothing like the original LPs, but they do sound like what the audience would have heard. The fidelity is great.</p>

<p>The other Japanese editions try to replicate the LPs (and get 95% of the way there). They are edited for time and drenched in added reverb. They are amazing aural experiences.</p>

<p>Now these can be bought, for about $40 apiece, easily enough. Both sets of Japanese CDs are out there. On the other hand, if you were to pick up The Complete Columbia Album Collection, which was produced to coincide with a Miles exhibition in France in 2009, you will not only get 52 miles albums, but it includes the Japanese versions of Agharta and Pangaea. Considering the Japanese imports would run to $80, paying a three times that amount for a further 50 albums, many of them classics, is good value (it's also the only place to get remastered 80's Miles). </p>

<p>Of course, it's never that simple. They included the 'LP; version of Agharta, all reverb and edited, and the 'live' version of Pangaea, with a clean sound. I think that's the best version of each album -- the reverb makes the more ferocious set even nastier, whereas the more ambient, entropy-effused Pangaea deserves the space to breathe, but, as the kids say, YMMV.</p>

<p>I too am hoping for some good future bootleg sets: the '71 European band which sprouted from the Live-Evil sets should be easy to cover; the On The Corner band is only on the rather stiff In Concert, and by all accounts they were pretty good by March '73, when they disbanded. As for the 'Funk Collective' of May 73 to 1975, hopefully we get some 1973 material (their Montreux set is partially available on DVD and a show at the Olympia got an official release in Europe), the '76 material with Gaunt on guitar, and then something from either the Japanese tour of '75 or the gigs around New York later than year (with yet another different sax player). </p>

<p>The only issue will be the naming of the tracks (since the Davis estate likes to garble them) and the fact that the 73, 74 and 1975 sets would appear to have very similar track listings.</p></p>
	<p><a class="util" href="#" onclick="replyTo('69965', 'Alan Moore'); return false;">Reply to this</a> <a class="util" href="#" onclick="Element.toggle('admin_comment_69965'); return false;">Admin</a>
	</p>

	
</div>
<div class="comment" id="comment_69970">


<b>Satish Robertson</b><br/>


<span class="sub">Feb 11, 2015  10:50am</span>
	
	<p><p>As a die hard fan of this particlar period of Miles Davis'output, I'd like to give kudos to you Angus for acknowledging the 40th anniversary of Agharta and Pangae. and for sharing your thoughts on Miles' music of this period as a whole. Julian Cope's article, though an impassioned and enjoyable read, is chock full of factual errors regarding this music. Your article, Angus, is much more well informed. </p>

<p>I would like to elaborate on the tune referred to as "Funk". In its humble beginnings during live performances in 1973, it started of as a funky little groove that Miles and the band would go into right after the Sly Stone-ish riff from "Right Off". You can hear this on several boots from that time (as well as video clips on youtube). Before long it became a piece Miles would introduce by playing a variation of the organ riff you hear at the start of "Tatu" at the start of Dark Magus disc 2. And for that matter, this piece actully appears twice on Dark Magus. You can hear it minus the organ intro and with a different groove as "Wili" part one on the first disc. It also serves as "Prelude" part 1 on Agharta, again with the opening organ riff but with a more uptempo and constantly evolving groove.</p></p>
	<p><a class="util" href="#" onclick="replyTo('69970', 'Satish Robertson'); return false;">Reply to this</a> <a class="util" href="#" onclick="Element.toggle('admin_comment_69970'); return false;">Admin</a>
	</p>

	
</div>
<div class="comment" id="comment_69971">


<b>Satish Robertson</b><br/>


<span class="sub">Feb 11, 2015  11:06am</span>
	
	<p><p>p.s. 
<br />Those of you interested in hearing the original LP mixes of Agharta and Pangea on CD (and you have the money to spare), you MUST get the 2013 blu spec CD2 editions. It's the original LP mix just like the 2006 editions but less shrill, more huge sounding, and infinitely crankable. As one who has these recordings on LP and several CD reissues, I can say the 2013 Blu spec CD2 is the only CD version which can compete with the vinyl. As for Dark Magus, some CD versions have better mastering than others but all do have the same monstrous mix as heard on vinyl.</p></p>
	<p><a class="util" href="#" onclick="replyTo('69971', 'Satish Robertson'); return false;">Reply to this</a> <a class="util" href="#" onclick="Element.toggle('admin_comment_69971'); return false;">Admin</a>
