<div class="comment" id="comment_70121">


<b>Griff Davies</b><br/>


<span class="sub">Feb 20, 2015  12:42pm</span>
	
	<p><p>Thanks for the interesting article! Apologies for seeming picky, but I would disagree with your description of the great LP 'Get Up With It' as being a 'mish mash' of old tunes recorded with 'no obvious purpose'. Actually three quarters of the double LP were recorded in 73 & 74 and clearly intended for release. I don't think it's fair to lump GUWI with 'Big Fun' which WAS acknowledged by MD at the time as being essentially a bunch of old outtakes.
<br />On a different note I agree with your observation that the band plays an echo of 'It's About That Time' during 'Zimbabwe' from 'Pangaea'. But it actually goes further than that: it's around the 34 minute mark on the CD version that Henderson and Foster play the rhythm from 'Black Satin', and Lucas joins in with those four stroked chords you mention - but as these chords also appeared (played on keyboard) during live versions of Black Satin in '72 (eg. on 'MD In Concert’), you could say that Lucas is actually playing an echo of an echo of 'It's About That Time'! </p></p>
	<p><a class="util" href="#" onclick="replyTo('70121', 'Griff Davies'); return false;">Reply to this</a> <a class="util" href="#" onclick="Element.toggle('admin_comment_70121'); return false;">Admin</a>
	</p>

	
